    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, full-bodied white wines can pair beautifully with certain red meats, especially when served with cream sauces or lighter preparations. Aged Chardonnay works well with roasted chicken or pork tenderloin, while Viognier complements grilled lamb with herbs. The key is matching the wine's weight and intensity to the dish—avoid delicate whites with heavily seasoned red meats, but embrace rich, oak-aged whites with lighter preparations.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when pairing white wine with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is choosing wines that are too light or delicate for rich, heavily sauced dishes, resulting in the wine being completely overwhelmed. Many people also serve white wines too cold, which mutes their flavors and prevents proper pairing harmony. Always consider the sauce and preparation method as much as the main ingredient, and serve fuller-bodied whites like Chardonnay at 50-55°F rather than ice-cold.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should white wine temperature change based on food pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—serving temperature significantly impacts how well a white wine pairs with food. Lighter wines like Pinot Grigio should be served colder (45-50°F) when paired with delicate appetizers or salads, while richer wines like oak-aged Chardonnay benefit from slightly warmer temperatures (50-55°F) to showcase their complexity alongside heartier dishes. Warmer serving temperatures allow the wine's flavors to better integrate with richer, more complex foods.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What white wines work best with spicy Asian cuisine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Off-dry white wines with good acidity and slight sweetness are ideal for spicy Asian dishes—try Riesling, Gewürztraminer, or Chenin Blanc. The residual sugar helps cool the palate from heat while the acidity refreshes between bites. Avoid bone-dry or heavily oaked whites, as they can clash with complex spice blends and make dishes taste more fiery than intended.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is white wine food pairing good for beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wine pairing is excellent for beginners because white wines are generally more forgiving and food-friendly than reds, with fewer tannins to clash with dishes. Start with versatile, high-acid wines like Sauvignon Blanc or Pinot Grigio that complement a wide range of foods. The basic principle of matching light wines with light dishes and fuller wines with richer foods provides a reliable foundation for developing your pairing skills.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between pairing oaked vs. unoaked white wines with food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Unoaked whites like Sauvignon Blanc or Chablis offer bright acidity and pure fruit flavors that pair beautifully with fresh, light dishes like salads, raw oysters, or grilled vegetables. Oaked whites like many Chardonnays provide richer, creamier textures with vanilla and spice notes that complement heavier dishes such as lobster with butter sauce, roasted chicken, or creamy pasta dishes. The oak treatment essentially determines whether the wine can stand up to richer preparations.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do you pair white wine with cheese effectively?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Match the intensity and texture of both the wine and cheese—crisp Sauvignon Blanc pairs beautifully with fresh goat cheese, while rich Chardonnay complements aged Gruyère or Camembert. Consider complementary flavors: Riesling's slight sweetness balances pungent blue cheeses, and mineral-driven wines like Sancerre enhance aged sheep's milk cheeses. Always serve the wine slightly warmer than usual to better showcase the pairing harmony.</p>
